Polish Stocks: Asseco, KGHM, Lotos, Orlen, Pekao Move in Warsaw

-- B y   P a w e l   K o z l o w s k i
-- 
2011-05-31T16:14:11Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-31/polish-stocks-asseco-kghm-lotos-orlen-pko-bank-are-active.html
Poland ’s WIG20 Index advanced for a
sixth day, adding 32.35, or 1.1 percent, to 2,903.61 at the 5:30
p.m. close in Warsaw. The measure fell 0.3 percent this month.  The following are among the most active stocks on the
Warsaw Stock Exchange today. Stock symbols follow company names.  Bank Pekao SA (PEO)  , majority-owned by UniCredit SpA,
increased 4.3 zloty, or 2.6 percent, to 169.7 zloty.  BRE Bank SA (BRE) 
, controlled by Commerzbank AG, advanced 3.6 zloty, or
1.1 percent, to 341.5 zloty.  Bank shares climbed across Europe as investors speculated
European officials will sanction additional financial assistance
for Greece.  Asseco Poland SA (ACP)   rose 1.5 zloty, or 2.9 percent,
to 52.95 zloty, climbing to the highest level in more than two
weeks. Central  Europe ’s biggest software developer had its
share-price estimate increased 7.9 percent to 68 zloty at
Raiffeisen Centrobank AG, which kept its “buy” recommendation.  KGHM Polska Miedz SA (KGH)  , the copper producer with the
biggest European mine output, gained 3.8 zloty, or 2 percent, to
192 zloty, closing at the highest level in almost a month, as
the price of the metal advanced.  PKN Orlen SA (PKN PW), Poland’s biggest oil company,
increased 1.2 zloty, or 2.3 percent, to 54 zloty.  Grupa Lotos SA (LTS) 
, the second-largest refiner, added 0.2 zloty, or 0.4
percent, to 46.7 zloty. Oil climbed on signals the European
Union will approve aid for  Greece , bolstering the euro against
the dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Pawel Kozlowski in Warsaw 
